payloadList.title: How Asthma Medicines Are Taken
payloadList.description: Nurse Nightingale teaches Big about the different ways he might take his asthma medicines, including overviews on inhalers, nebulizers, and spacers.

payloadList.title: Intro to Asthma
payloadList.description: Coughing, wheezing, and trouble getting a deep breath stop the Big Bad Wolf from blowing down the 3 Little Pigs' house of straw. Jiggs the Pig steps up to help him get to the doctor to find out what's gone wrong with his world-famous huff and puff.

payloadList.title: Signs & Symptoms
payloadList.description: This episode covers �the�"signs" and "symptoms"�of asthma. These are the things that you can see,�hear, or feel -- like a cough, wheeze, or tightnes�in the chest.

payloadList.title: The Examination
payloadList.description: Before the doctor can tell Big if he has asthma,�he has to do an examination. �This video lets�kids know what to expect during the examination�and assures them "it won't take long, and�it doesn't hurt a bit."

payloadList.title: Diagnosis
payloadList.description: Dr. Yan gives Big his official diagnosis: asthma. He explains that while asthma can't be cured, it can be controlled and he introduces Big and Jiggs to the "Asthma Action Plan."

payloadList.title: Triggers
payloadList.description: Big learns that "triggers" -- things like smoke, pollution, pet dander, and pollen -- can make his asthma worse or even bring on an asthma attack.

payloadList.title: Resuce & Maintenance Medicines
payloadList.description: Along with his mom and dad, Big learns about "rescue" and "maintenance" medicines for asthma, how they're different, and why they're both very important.

payloadList.title: What is Diabetes?
payloadList.description: What does the pancreas do? �Why does your body need insulin? What happens if you have too much or too little sugar (aka glucose) in your blood. �Find out in this short animated video that answers the question "What is Diabetes?"

payloadList.title: What is Type 1 Diabetes?
payloadList.description: Type 1 diabetes is when your pancreas makes very little insulin or no insulin at all. �It is usually found in kids and young adults, which is why it used be be called juvenile diabetes.
